Itis quite clear that the quarrel between the Calixtines and the Taborites is especially on account of the doctrine of the Lord's Supper, wlich the latter absolutely refused to abendon. At the general synod of Progne (1444), they stated their position as follows:

Et idco necessarium est circa hoc (sacramentum) evangelium maxime attendere eteius verum sensum scrutari scduccionem callidam diaboli iu hoc summopere declinand0, quia Ductor Euartgeficas· spiritu prophetico dicit, quomodocumque spuria vitulamina Antichristi preciduntur, tamen non cessabunt iterum pullulare, nisi eorum radix · fuerit suffossa, que est heretica seduccio circa Eucharistie sacramentum, ad cuius seduccionis ecclesianam, prout tactum cst, noster labor suit et est.

And therefore, when the ‘Magister’ of Prague (a Calixtine), put the question to the Taborites:

An credimus quod ipse Christus estin Sacramento Altaris non solum spiritualiter per quandam graciam solam ab ipso corpore naturali Christi condistiuctam, nec solum sacramentaliter et figuraliter, sed ultra hoc quantumcumque cst Christus lesus per resurrectionem suam gloriosus, spititualis et divinus, veritate tamen sui corporis et natura permanente est in eodem sacramento:

They answered:

Istam proposictonem nos sacerdotes antedicti concedimus, scd non ad falsum sensum hereticorum nolentium concedere naturalem distiaccioaem inter sacramentam altaris visibile et corpus Christi naturali.
